{"cursor":"4647","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\n'Bioelectromagnetism' (sometimes equated with 'bioelectricity') refers to the\nelectrical,or electromagnetic fields produced by living cells, tissues or\norganisms. Examples include the cell membrane potential and the electric\ncurrents that flow in nerves and muscles, as a result of action potentials.\n'Bioelectromagnetism' is somewhat similar to bioelectromagnetics, which deals\nwith the effect on life from external electromagnetism; yet such an effect also\nfalls under the definition of 'bioelectromagnetism'. Jaakko Malmivuo, Robert\nPlonsey, [http://www.bem.fi/book/01/01.htm Bioelectromagnetism: Principles and\nApplications of Bioelectric and Biomagnetic Fields.] Oxford University Press.\nNew York, Oxford. 1995. Introduction.\n","linknr":163,"url":"Bioelectricity","recorded":1362485591,"links":21,"instances":["biology"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Biophysics","Electromagnetism","Physiology"],"headings":["Description","See also","References","External links","Bibliography"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/52/Merge-arrows.svg/50px-Merge-arrows.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/52/Merge-arrows.svg/50px-Merge-arrows.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8b/Nuvola_apps_kalzium.svg/28px-Nuvola_apps_kalzium.svg.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/vector/images/search-ltr.png?303-4","//bits.wikimedia.org/images/wikimedia-button.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/poweredby_mediawiki_88x31.png"],"tags":[["cell","biology"]],"members":["cell"],"related":["Electromagnetic_field","Cell_(biology)","Biological_tissue","Organism","Membrane_potential","Electric_current","Nerve","Muscle","Action_potential","Bioelectromagnetics","Action_potentials","Voltage-gated_ion_channel","Electrochemical_gradient","Electrophysiology","Italy","Physician","Physicist","Luigi_Galvani","Frog","Static_electricity","G